Good 👍 I’ll now explain the VPC creation + EC2 connection steps correctly, clearly, and in proper order, and then briefly explain the logic behind each step so you fully understand it (not just memorize it).

I’ll structure this in:

Core VPC Setup (Step-by-step)

Why each step is required

Common mistakes

✅ PART 1 — Step-by-Step: Creating VPC & Connecting EC2
🔹 Step 1: Create a VPC

Go to:

AWS Console → VPC → Create VPC → Choose “VPC only”

Enter:

Name: Custom-VPC

IPv4 CIDR block: 10.0.0.0/16

Click Create VPC

🔎 Why /16?

10.0.0.0/16 gives 65,536 IP addresses.
This allows future scaling.

🔹 Step 2: Create Subnets (Public & Private)

Go to:

VPC → Subnets → Create Subnet

Create:

Public Subnet

VPC: Custom-VPC

AZ: us-east-1a (example)

CIDR: 10.0.1.0/24

Private Subnet

VPC: Custom-VPC

AZ: us-east-1a

CIDR: 10.0.2.0/24

Click Create.

🔎 Why /24?

Each /24 gives 256 IPs (251 usable).
Good for subnet-level segmentation.

🔹 Step 3: Create Internet Gateway (IGW)

Go to:

VPC → Internet Gateways → Create

Name: Custom-IGW

Attach to Custom-VPC

🔹 Step 4: Create Route Tables

You need 2 route tables.

🟢 Public Route Table

VPC → Route Tables → Create

Select Custom-VPC

Edit routes:

Add:

Destination: 0.0.0.0/0
Target: Internet Gateway

Then:

Subnet Associations → Associate with Public Subnet

🔴 Private Route Table

Create new route table.

Keep only:

Destination: 10.0.0.0/16
Target: local

Associate with Private Subnet.

(If you want internet from private subnet → use NAT Gateway, not IGW.)

🔹 Step 5: Enable Auto-Assign Public IP (Important)

Go to:

Subnets → Select Public Subnet → Edit subnet settings

Enable:

✔ Auto-assign public IPv4 address

🔹 Step 6: Configure Security Groups

Create Security Group:

Inbound Rules:

SSH (22) → Your IP only

HTTP (80) → 0.0.0.0/0

HTTPS (443) → 0.0.0.0/0

Attach this SG to EC2.

🔹 Step 7: Launch EC2

Public EC2:

Subnet: Public subnet

Auto-assign public IP: Enabled

Security group: Web-SG

Private EC2:

Subnet: Private subnet

No public IP

Proper internal security group

🔹 Step 8: Testing

Public EC2:
✔ Can access internet
✔ Can SSH from your IP

Private EC2:
❌ No direct internet
✔ Can connect internally

✅ PART 2 — Why Each Component Exists

Now understand this conceptually:

VPC

Virtual network inside AWS.

Subnet

Subdivision of VPC.

Internet Gateway

Allows communication between VPC and internet.

Route Table

Controls traffic direction.

Security Group

Instance-level firewall.

NAT Gateway (Optional)

Allows private subnet outbound internet.

🚨 Common Mistakes Students Make

Forgetting IGW attachment

Forgetting route table association

Not enabling auto public IP

Security group blocking port 22

NACL blocking traffic

Using wrong CIDR

🧠 Important Concept

Public vs Private Subnet is NOT a checkbox.

It depends on:

Route table configuration

Whether 0.0.0.0/0 points to IGW

If route table has IGW → Public subnet
If not → Private subnet

