Good 👍 this is the correct way to ask.

Now I will give you exact console steps — which tab, which button, what to click — no skipping, no shortcuts.

I’ll assume:

Region: us-east-1

Goal: 1 Public subnet + 1 Private subnet

Launch EC2 and connect

Follow exactly.

✅ PART 1 — Create VPC
Step 1

Login to AWS Console

In search bar (top), type: VPC

Click VPC (under Services)

Step 2 — Create VPC

On left sidebar → click Your VPCs

Click Create VPC (top right)

Now you will see 2 options:

VPC and more

VPC only

Select: VPC only

Fill:

Name tag → Custom-VPC

IPv4 CIDR block → 10.0.0.0/16

Tenancy → Default

Click Create VPC

Wait until status = Available.

✅ PART 2 — Create Subnets
Step 3 — Create Public Subnet

Left sidebar → Click Subnets

Click Create subnet

Fill:

VPC ID → Select Custom-VPC

Subnet name → Public-Subnet

Availability Zone → choose one (ex: us-east-1a)

IPv4 CIDR block → 10.0.1.0/24

Click Create subnet

Step 4 — Create Private Subnet

Again click Create subnet

Fill:

VPC ID → Custom-VPC

Subnet name → Private-Subnet

Availability Zone → same AZ (or different if you want)

IPv4 CIDR block → 10.0.2.0/24

Click Create subnet

At this point:
🚨 BOTH subnets are PRIVATE.

✅ PART 3 — Create Internet Gateway
Step 5

Left sidebar → Click Internet Gateways

Click Create internet gateway

Fill:

Name tag → Custom-IGW

Click Create internet gateway

Step 6 — Attach IGW to VPC

After creation:

Select the IGW

Click Actions

Click Attach to VPC

Select Custom-VPC

Click Attach internet gateway

Now VPC has internet connection ability.

✅ PART 4 — Make Public Subnet Truly Public

Right now IGW exists but subnets are not using it.

Step 7 — Create Public Route Table

Left sidebar → Click Route Tables

Click Create route table

Fill:

Name → Public-Route-Table

VPC → Custom-VPC

Click Create route table

Step 8 — Add Internet Route

Select Public-Route-Table

Go to Routes tab

Click Edit routes

Click Add route

Fill:

Destination → 0.0.0.0/0

Target → Select Internet Gateway

Choose your Custom-IGW

Click Save changes

Step 9 — Associate Public Subnet

Still inside Public-Route-Table

Go to Subnet associations tab

Click Edit subnet associations

Select Public-Subnet

Click Save associations

Now:

✔ Public-Subnet is PUBLIC
❌ Private-Subnet is still private

✅ PART 5 — Enable Public IP Auto Assign
Step 10

Go to Subnets

Select Public-Subnet

Click Actions

Click Edit subnet settings

Enable:

✔ Auto-assign public IPv4 address

Click Save

✅ PART 6 — Launch EC2
Step 11

Search → EC2

Click Instances

Click Launch instances

Fill:

Name → Public-EC2

AMI → Amazon Linux

Instance type → t2.micro

Key pair → Select or create

Step 12 — Network Settings

Click Edit in Network section.

Set:

VPC → Custom-VPC

Subnet → Public-Subnet

Auto-assign public IP → Enable

Security group → Create new

Add inbound rules:

SSH → My IP

HTTP → 0.0.0.0/0

Click Launch instance

✅ PART 7 — Test

Go to Instances → Select Public-EC2

Check:

Does it have Public IPv4 address?

If yes:

Use:

ssh -i key.pem ec2-user@public-ip

You should connect.

🔴 Why You Were Confused

Because AWS DOES NOT give button called:

“Make public subnet”

“Make private subnet”

It depends only on:

Route Table → 0.0.0.0/0 → IGW

That’s it.

